###How to fix the Common Vulnerabilities issue of CVE-2018-15919
CVE-2018-15919 is a vulnerability in the Apache HTTP Server that allows an attacker to execute arbitrary code on the server by sending a specially crafted request. The vulnerability is caused by a flaw in the way the server handles HTTP/2 requests.

To fix the vulnerability, you should upgrade your Apache HTTP Server to a version that includes the security patch for CVE-2018-15919. You can find the latest security patches for Apache HTTP Server on the Apache Software Foundation website.

CVE-2018-15919 belongs to the OWASP Top 10 Web 2021 category of Injection. Injection flaws, such as SQL injection and cross-site scripting (XSS), occur when unvalidated or malicious data is sent to an interpreter as part of a command or query. The attacker's hostile data can trick the interpreter into executing unintended commands or accessing data without proper authorization.

Here are some additional steps you can take to protect your Apache HTTP Server from attack:

* Use a firewall to restrict access to the server.
* Enable authentication and authorization for all resources.
* Use a web application firewall (WAF) to block known attack vectors.
* Keep your software up to date with the latest security patches.

By following these steps, you can help to protect your Apache HTTP Server from attack and keep your data safe.
